00:37:44,485 --> 00:37:49,885
Harmonic connection between
all living beings everywhere, even the stars.

491
00:37:50,596 --> 00:37:52,418
Is this a school?

492
00:37:52,581 --> 00:37:55,679
Yeah, the school of
Screw You and Take All Your Damn Money.

493
00:37:55,845 --> 00:37:57,633
-Yeah.
-Yeah, we're top of the class.

494
00:37:57,796 --> 00:37:59,105
Not!

495
00:38:01,413 --> 00:38:02,841
It's a business.

496
00:38:05,380 --> 00:38:07,868
Pockets.
GIRL 2: Okay, let's go.

497
00:38:08,037 --> 00:38:09,597
Let's go, let's go.
WALLACE: Pockets.

498
00:38:10,436 --> 00:38:11,516
BOY 1:
Oh, man. Get up.

499
00:38:11,684 --> 00:38:13,594
[CHATTERING]

500
00:38:15,492 --> 00:38:16,670
WALLACE:
Peanut, well done.

501
00:38:17,893 --> 00:38:19,486
I got eyes in the back of my head.

502
00:38:20,421 --> 00:38:22,209
<i>Good job. Gracias, amigo.</i>

503
00:38:22,373 --> 00:38:24,511
Chain is only as strong...

504
00:38:24,933 --> 00:38:26,177
...as its weakest link.

505
00:38:28,773 --> 00:38:30,202
Come on, Arthur.

506
00:38:30,533 --> 00:38:32,028
That's chump change.

507
00:38:32,197 --> 00:38:35,394
You got Washington Square.
That was my spot for 10 years.

508
00:38:39,365 --> 00:38:42,365
Go ahead, before I change my mind.

509
00:38:46,501 --> 00:38:48,574
You kids are gonna put me
in the poorhouse.

510
00:38:49,509 --> 00:38:52,324
All right, little mice,
scurry back to your holes. Go, go.

511
00:38:54,853 --> 00:38:57,569
Harmonic dreams, sweet children.

512
00:39:05,219 --> 00:39:07,042
[PLAYING VAN MORRISON'S
"MOONDANCE" ON HARMONICA]

513
00:39:45,732 --> 00:39:50,042
[PLAYING MARK MANCINA'S
"BARI IMPROV"]

514
00:41:21,509 --> 00:41:23,549
ARTHUR:
Roxanne. Man, I'm gonna kill him.

515
00:41:50,725 --> 00:41:52,580
WALLACE:
You know what's out there?

516
00:41:53,188 --> 00:41:55,228
A series of higher tones.

517
00:41:55,397 --> 00:41:56,858
It's arranged by nature.

518
00:41:57,029 --> 00:42:00,924
It's governed by the laws of physics
of the whole universe.

519
00:42:02,277 --> 00:42:04,579
It's an overtone, it's an energy,
it's a wavelength.

520
00:42:04,741 --> 00:42:09,083
And if you're not riding it, good Lordy,
you'll never hear it.

521
00:42:09,253 --> 00:42:11,195
Where do you think it comes from?

522
00:42:12,932 --> 00:42:14,176
What I hear.

523
00:42:14,757 --> 00:42:18,106
I think it comes from all around you, really.
I mean, it's...

524
00:42:18,276 --> 00:42:20,032
Comes through us, some of us.

525
00:42:22,180 --> 00:42:25,115
It's invisible, but... But you feel it.

526
00:42:26,020 --> 00:42:27,711
So only some of us can hear it?

527
00:42:29,284 --> 00:42:31,172
Only some of us are listening.

528
00:42:33,861 --> 00:42:36,097
Do you think my parents are listening?

529
00:42:36,933 --> 00:42:38,820
I hear you, kid.

530
00:42:41,669 --> 00:42:42,617
Like:

531
00:42:42,789 --> 00:42:44,098
[STRUMS GUITAR]

532
00:42:44,645 --> 00:42:46,171
Yeah.

533
00:42:49,956 --> 00:42:51,517
WOMAN:
Are you hearing a word I'm saying?

534
00:42:51,685 --> 00:42:52,961
[CHATTERING]

535
00:42:55,654 --> 00:42:56,995
Louis.

536
00:42:57,733 --> 00:43:00,450
Come on.
It's about time I met your family.

537
00:43:01,605 --> 00:43:04,126
[CHRIS TRAPPER'S "THIS TIME"
PLAYING IN DISTANCE]

538
00:43:04,805 --> 00:43:08,154
Listen, Jen,
maybe this isn't such a good idea.

539
00:43:09,094 --> 00:43:10,076
Grow up.

540
00:43:10,533 --> 00:43:11,941
Come on.

541
00:43:13,765 --> 00:43:14,976
-Come on.
-"Grow up."

542
00:43:16,741 --> 00:43:19,163
<i>[SINGING ON VIDEO]
The angel on the stairs</i>

543
00:43:19,333 --> 00:43:22,716
JEN: Are all Irish people this loud?
Yeah.

544
00:43:22,886 --> 00:43:25,307
<i>Will tell you I was there</i>

545
00:43:27,782 --> 00:43:31,197
<i>Under the front porch light</i>

546
00:43:31,366 --> 00:43:34,180
<i>On a mystery night</i>

547
00:43:40,294 --> 00:43:44,800
<i>I been sitting
Watching life pass from the sidelines</i>

548
00:43:45,733 --> 00:43:46,682
MAN:
Hey, Louis.

549
00:43:46,853 --> 00:43:48,741
<i>Been waiting for a dream</i>

550
00:43:48,902 --> 00:43:52,448
<i>To seep in through my blinds</i>

551
00:43:53,958 --> 00:43:56,260
NICK:
Hey, Marshall, your brother's here.

552
00:43:56,646 --> 00:43:57,627
Louis.

553
00:44:00,229 --> 00:44:01,637
Hey, Nick.

554
00:44:02,022 --> 00:44:03,516
<i>Could I get you off my mind</i>

555
00:44:04,037 --> 00:44:07,584
JEN:
Oh, my God. Is that you?

556
00:44:07,750 --> 00:44:09,758
<i>This time?</i>

557
00:44:10,662 --> 00:44:12,997
When were you gonna tell me
you're in a band?

558
00:44:15,302 --> 00:44:18,564
I'm sure there's a lot of things
our Louis hasn't told you, darling.

559
00:44:18,725 --> 00:44:21,595
-Like who did you write the song for?
-I told you this is a mistake.

560
00:44:22,117 --> 00:44:24,604
That's it, go on. Walk out on us again.

561
00:44:27,461 --> 00:44:29,632
Eh, Lou?
LOUIS: Say what you gotta say, Marshall.

562
00:44:29,796 --> 00:44:31,684
-Say what you have to say.
-No, go on.

563
00:44:31,845 --> 00:44:33,852
Come on, say it.
MARSHALL: That the best you got?

564
00:44:34,022 --> 00:44:35,614
-Say it.
-That the best you got?

565
00:44:35,781 --> 00:44:37,920
-Come on. Hit me. Come on, hit me.
-Come on.

566
00:44:38,085 --> 00:44:40,157
Feel what? Come on. Hit me.

567
00:44:41,445 --> 00:44:42,689
I'm suffocating here.

568
00:44:43,429 --> 00:44:45,665
<i>The things I left behind</i>

569
00:44:49,222 --> 00:44:50,650
You all right, man?

570
00:44:52,645 --> 00:44:54,271
You all right, man?

571
00:44:54,917 --> 00:44:56,575
Welcome to the Connelly clan.

572
00:44:56,741 --> 00:44:58,465
[MARSHALL LAUGHS]

573
00:45:03,974 --> 00:45:05,533
Jennifer.

574
00:45:29,925 --> 00:45:32,740
You know, it was good
having the old Louis back in there...

575
00:45:33,253 --> 00:45:35,523
...even if it was only for a second.

576
00:45:37,413 --> 00:45:38,843
Louie...

577
00:45:39,270 --> 00:45:41,823
...aren't you supposed to be in the car
with the girl...

578
00:45:41,989 --> 00:45:44,062
...as she drives off into the sunset?

579
00:45:52,197 --> 00:45:54,652
You'll get your suit dirty
sitting there, man.

580
00:45:57,638 --> 00:46:00,933
[MARK MANCINA'S
"5-NOTE TRANSITION" PLAYING]

581
00:46:02,790 --> 00:46:04,928
[PHONE RINGING]

582
00:46:07,238 --> 00:46:08,186
[ANSWERING MACHINE BEEPS]

583
00:46:08,359 --> 00:46:10,398
<i>WOMAN [OVER PHONE]:
This is a message for Lyla Novacek.</i>

584
00:46:10,566 --> 00:46:12,606
<i>Please call Good Samaritan Hospital.</i>

585
00:46:12,774 --> 00:46:16,090
<i>I'm calling about your father,
Thomas Novacek.</i>

586
00:46:25,318 --> 00:46:27,554
THOMAS:
I wasn't sure you were going to come.

587
00:46:28,646 --> 00:46:30,980
My will is in the top drawer
of the desk in my study.

588
00:46:31,143 --> 00:46:33,564
Dad, stop, come on.

589
00:46:33,734 --> 00:46:35,806
THOMAS:
Lyla, please.

590
00:46:35,974 --> 00:46:37,697
There's more.

591
00:46:44,198 --> 00:46:49,697
All I ever wanted was for you
to have all that promise, all that life.

592
00:46:50,182 --> 00:46:52,037
But you were so young.

593
00:46:52,454 --> 00:46:54,462
We had so much work to do.

594
00:46:54,631 --> 00:46:57,762
-You weren't ready.
-That's plenty, Dad. Really.

595
00:46:58,535 --> 00:47:00,510
I mean, a baby.

596
00:47:00,678 --> 00:47:02,434
That baby, he could have hurt you.

597
00:47:02,598 --> 00:47:04,965
[MARK MANCINA'S
"HOSPITAL PT. 2" PLAYING]

598
00:47:05,414 --> 00:47:09,537
He could've hurt you, and I...
I wasn't gonna let that happen, Lyla.

599
00:47:14,789 --> 00:47:16,797
I made a choice for us.

600
00:47:20,486 --> 00:47:22,274
Oh, my God.

601
00:47:24,230 --> 00:47:25,408
<i>THOMAS:
A choice for us.</i>

602
00:47:27,301 --> 00:47:28,796
Wait....

603
00:47:33,733 --> 00:47:35,359
<i>THOMAS:
I'm sorry.</i>

604
00:47:40,037 --> 00:47:41,281
Where?

605
00:47:44,229 --> 00:47:45,986
Where is he?

606
00:47:46,757 --> 00:47:50,172
-I didn't mean...
-Where is he?

607
00:47:50,598 --> 00:47:51,775
I don't know.

608
00:47:53,734 --> 00:47:55,327
I don't.

609
00:47:57,286 --> 00:48:00,253
[PLAYING MICHAEL HEDGES'
"RITUAL DANCE"]

610
00:48:03,942 --> 00:48:06,495
<i>WALLACE: You gotta love music
more than you love food.</i>

611
00:48:07,398 --> 00:48:10,912
More than life. More than yourself.

612
00:48:17,061 --> 00:48:18,239
You feel it?

613
00:48:21,701 --> 00:48:22,684
Then show me.

614
00:48:23,398 --> 00:48:25,286
Play it for your parents.

615
00:49:12,807 --> 00:49:14,268
You're flying, kid.

616
00:49:14,439 --> 00:49:16,927
[CROWD CLAPPING]

617
00:49:23,910 --> 00:49:25,405
WALLACE:
Yeah!

618
00:49:25,574 --> 00:49:27,614
You know what I'm thinking?

619
00:49:28,454 --> 00:49:30,910
You're supposed to say,
"What are you thinking, Wizard?"

620
00:49:31,078 --> 00:49:33,282
"What are you thinking, Wizard?"

621
00:49:33,447 --> 00:49:35,781
I teach you everything I know for free.

622
00:49:35,943 --> 00:49:38,724
You get Roxanne.
You get my corner of the park.

623
00:49:39,143 --> 00:49:42,405
You get to keep half your tips.
We're like a team.

624
00:49:43,879 --> 00:49:45,766
There's something wrong
with that picture.

625
00:49:46,182 --> 00:49:47,197
What?

626
00:49:47,943 --> 00:49:51,139
I don't think performing in parks
and street corners is gonna be enough.

627
00:49:51,302 --> 00:49:52,479
It won't?

628
00:49:55,526 --> 00:49:58,723
Evan, we're gonna need
to get you a new name.

629
00:49:58,886 --> 00:50:00,576
Something with a little more pop.

630
00:50:00,997 --> 00:50:04,445
What do you wanna be in the world?
In the whole world, what do you wanna be?

631
00:50:04,614 --> 00:50:06,655
Close your eyes and think about that.

632
00:50:08,742 --> 00:50:10,171
Found.

633
00:50:15,206 --> 00:50:16,515
Doesn't have enough yin.

634
00:50:17,255 --> 00:50:19,295
-Little more yang, you know?
-Yeah.

635
00:50:19,462 --> 00:50:20,575
Yeah, let's....

636
00:50:20,742 --> 00:50:22,236
[TRUCK HORN HONKING]

637
00:50:22,406 --> 00:50:26,203
Talk about wishful thinking. Look at that.

638
00:50:29,222 --> 00:50:31,197
What name stands out to you
on that, huh?

639
00:50:31,366 --> 00:50:32,348
Beach?

640
00:50:32,518 --> 00:50:34,852
It's a good name for a band,
but not for a performer.

641
00:50:35,014 --> 00:50:37,829
You can't say, "Please welcome Beach."
No, no.

642
00:50:37,990 --> 00:50:42,114
August Rush. August Rush.
Doesn't that warm you up a little bit?

643
00:50:42,534 --> 00:50:45,731
I can see it.
"Wizard Productions presents...

644
00:50:45,895 --> 00:50:48,644
...the number-one heat wave:

645
00:50:48,807 --> 00:50:52,123
"August Rush!"

646
00:50:52,294 --> 00:50:54,750
-Yeah.
-Yeah. Me!

647
00:50:54,918 --> 00:50:57,471
-August, August, August.
-It gives me a rush.

648
00:50:57,638 --> 00:51:00,802
That gives me chills. The hair
on the back of my neck's standing up.

649
00:51:00,966 --> 00:51:02,373
-Really?
-Yeah, look at that.

650
00:51:02,534 --> 00:51:03,909
Quick, check it out. Yeah.

651
00:51:04,070 --> 00:51:07,551
-I'm flying! I'm flying!
-Yeah. August! August Rush.

652
00:51:07,719 --> 00:51:09,923
-August.
-August Rush. August Rush.

653
00:51:10,086 --> 00:51:11,069
That's you.

654
00:51:11,431 --> 00:51:13,732
<i>WALLACE: August. August.
AUGUST: August Rush, August Rush.</i>

655
00:51:15,687 --> 00:51:18,240
[LUCAS REYNOLDS'
"SOMETHING INSIDE" PLAYING]

656
00:51:56,295 --> 00:51:57,375
[THUNDER CRASHES]

657
00:51:57,543 --> 00:51:59,747
<i>LIZZY: New York, Lyla?
What are you doing in New York?</i>

658
00:51:59,911 --> 00:52:02,562
Lizzy, I mean,
I've always felt that he was alive.

659
00:52:02,727 --> 00:52:07,812
I'd see kids that would be his age
and I'd imagine what he'd look like.

660
00:52:07,975 --> 00:52:10,626
<i>-Big blue eyes like his dad and...
-Oh, my God, Lyla.</i>

661
00:52:10,791 --> 00:52:15,046
Lizzy, I used to lie in bed at night
and I swear I could hear him.

662
00:52:15,207 --> 00:52:18,055
<i>-I swear I could hear him.
-Lyla, calm down.</i>

663
00:52:18,215 --> 00:52:21,729
Calm down? How can I be calm?
How can I be calm?

664
00:52:21,896 --> 00:52:25,026
I've been calm for over 10 years
and look where it's gotten me.

665
00:52:25,191 --> 00:52:27,579
<i>Lyla, you're losing it.</i>

666
00:52:27,816 --> 00:52:30,914
You're right. And maybe it's about time.

667
00:52:31,080 --> 00:52:32,704
<i>Don't do anything crazy, okay?</i>

668
00:52:32,870 --> 00:52:37,027
<i>We're on our honeymoon, but we're leaving.
We'll get there as soon as we can, okay?</i>

669
00:52:55,655 --> 00:52:58,405
Okay, Jack, he's worth three times
what you're offering him.

670
00:52:58,567 --> 00:53:00,290
-Wallace...
-You heard him in the park!

671
00:53:00,456 --> 00:53:01,665
You're a pain in the ass.

672
00:53:01,831 --> 00:53:05,092
-Two-fifty if he can play for two hours.
-No, five or he walks.

673
00:53:05,255 --> 00:53:09,860
-Five hundred? I'll give him 250...
-Five hundred or he walks, all right?

674
00:53:10,022 --> 00:53:10,971
JACK:
He walks?

675
00:53:11,143 --> 00:53:13,281
WALLACE:
We have lightning in a bottle, Jack.

676
00:53:13,446 --> 00:53:15,868
No, there's no parents. I'm his guardian.

677
00:53:16,039 --> 00:53:19,105
No, I'm his representation,
that's why I'm making the deal.

678
00:53:19,270 --> 00:53:20,929
WOMAN:
May I help you?

679
00:53:21,319 --> 00:53:23,458
I'm trying to find my son.
WOMAN: Hold on a second.

680
00:53:24,167 --> 00:53:25,760
Name?

681
00:53:30,855 --> 00:53:32,764
GIRL 1:
Mommy.

682
00:53:33,703 --> 00:53:36,517
[MARK MANCINA'S
"PLAYGROUND" PLAYING]

683
00:53:38,344 --> 00:53:40,198
Mommy.

684
00:53:42,918 --> 00:53:44,326
I don't know.

685
00:53:45,703 --> 00:53:48,158
GIRL 2: Mom.
GIRL 3: Mommy.

686
00:53:57,800 --> 00:53:59,840
Mommy, look at me.

687
00:54:00,007 --> 00:54:02,397
I'm sorry, ma'am, we're closing.

688
00:54:03,687 --> 00:54:07,331
Please, I just... I wanna know his name.

689
00:54:08,071 --> 00:54:13,057
To even consider re-establishing contact
with a child, there is a detailed process.

690
00:54:13,223 --> 00:54:17,696
I don't care about your process! Okay?

691
00:54:33,223 --> 00:54:37,533
WOMAN: Ma'am, we're closed.
Come back tomorrow.

692
00:54:40,935 --> 00:54:42,594
<i>LOUIS:
Lyla.</i>

693
00:54:43,592 --> 00:54:44,998
<i>Novacek.</i>

694
00:54:47,720 --> 00:54:50,437
<i>LYLA [ON RECORDING]: Hi, this is Lyla...
LIZZY [ON RECORDING]: And Lizzy.</i>

695
00:54:50,600 --> 00:54:53,120
<i>LYLA & LIZZY: And we're not here
right now, so leave a message.</i>

696
00:54:53,288 --> 00:54:54,814
[MACHINE BEEPS]

697
00:55:12,681 --> 00:55:14,142
WALLACE:
Arthur!

698
00:55:14,983 --> 00:55:17,121
What'd I tell you
about talking to strangers?

699
00:55:17,287 --> 00:55:20,603
-Yeah, what's your name?
-My name is Mr. Jeffries, and yours?

700
00:55:21,095 --> 00:55:23,234
Arthur. We ain't strangers now.

701
00:55:23,751 --> 00:55:27,777
Look, Mr. Wallace,
I'm here making my normal rounds.

702
00:55:27,943 --> 00:55:29,437
I'm trying to find these kids.

703
00:55:29,608 --> 00:55:32,706
This girl, her name is Geralda.
She should be about 14 now.

704
00:55:32,871 --> 00:55:34,245
Don't know her, Mr. Jeffries.

705
00:55:34,407 --> 00:55:37,309
Okay, well, maybe you can help me
with this young man.

706
00:55:37,480 --> 00:55:41,222
Little boy that came up missing recently
and his name is Evan Taylor.

707
00:55:42,023 --> 00:55:44,095
He's about 12.

708
00:55:46,151 --> 00:55:49,631
And what if I find this Evan
and I turn him over to you?

709
00:55:50,183 --> 00:55:53,925
What then? You don't care about a kid
after he's in the system.

710
00:55:54,087 --> 00:55:57,535
-It's not like that...
-Oh, I know exactly what it's like.

711
00:55:57,703 --> 00:56:01,533
You don't follow up.
And you throw him from place to place.

712
00:56:01,703 --> 00:56:05,150
Eventually, you end up in a place
where they kick the crap out of you.

713
00:56:05,575 --> 00:56:10,016
Go to bed at night
and he tries to close his eyes, ears.

714
00:56:10,183 --> 00:56:11,808
Shut out the world.

715
00:56:11,976 --> 00:56:15,358
What happens to that kid?
What do you think he hears?

716
00:56:15,943 --> 00:56:17,569
What do you think he hears?

717
00:56:19,239 --> 00:56:21,279
-Nothing.
-Nothing. Nothing at all.

718
00:56:24,871 --> 00:56:25,952
Are you all right?

719
00:56:26,535 --> 00:56:28,030
-Yeah, I'm cool.
-He's good.

720
00:56:36,584 --> 00:56:38,559
<i>MAN:
Fourteenth Precinct, Sergeant O'Malley.</i>

721
00:56:39,337 --> 00:56:41,791
WALLACE:
No. That doesn't cut it.

722
00:56:41,960 --> 00:56:44,099
[PLAYING MARK MANCINA'S
"WIND UP"]

723
00:56:44,263 --> 00:56:47,198
No! Oh, is that final?

724
00:56:47,368 --> 00:56:50,629
Okay, well, here's my final offer:
We're history!

