01:15:52,044 --> 01:15:53,537
Would you like that?

955
01:15:54,412 --> 01:15:56,778
Well, good. Good.

956
01:15:56,940 --> 01:15:58,532
How many people will hear it?

957
01:16:01,195 --> 01:16:04,806
Well, it would be performed in Central Park,
on the Great Lawn.

958
01:16:04,972 --> 01:16:05,954
A hundred?

959
01:16:07,084 --> 01:16:08,906
Much more. Thousands.

960
01:16:09,707 --> 01:16:14,082
Okay. Because I need to play it
to a lot of people. Lots and lots.

961
01:16:14,252 --> 01:16:15,462
[PEOPLE CHUCKLING]

962
01:16:15,628 --> 01:16:17,253
We'll see what we can do to help.

963
01:16:19,660 --> 01:16:25,442
DEAN: August, three artists will be
performing, and you will be featured last.

964
01:16:26,028 --> 01:16:28,297
[MARK MANCINA'S
"JUILLIARD MONTAGE" PLAYING]

965
01:16:36,204 --> 01:16:37,927
<i>How do you do it?</i>

966
01:16:38,316 --> 01:16:41,545
How does the music come to you?

967
01:16:43,595 --> 01:16:45,286
<i>AUGUST:
I just hear it.</i>

968
01:16:49,067 --> 01:16:50,824
Sometimes I wake up and it's there...

969
01:16:50,988 --> 01:16:53,704
...or I hear it
when I'm walking down the street.

970
01:16:55,020 --> 01:16:59,459
[MARK MANCINA'S
"JUILLIARD MONTAGE" PLAYING]

971
01:17:00,523 --> 01:17:02,977
<i>It's like someone's calling out to me.</i>

972
01:17:03,850 --> 01:17:06,404
Writing it all down
is like I'm calling back to them.

973
01:17:06,571 --> 01:17:07,782
Who?

974
01:17:09,227 --> 01:17:11,332
The ones who gave me the music.

975
01:17:18,379 --> 01:17:20,234
MARSHALL:
You sure you're ready for this, Louis?

976
01:17:20,395 --> 01:17:21,639
Are you?

977
01:17:47,371 --> 01:17:50,567
[ORCHESTRA PLAYING MARK MANCINA'S
"RHAPSODY REHEARSAL"]

978
01:18:19,468 --> 01:18:21,093
Bravo, August!

979
01:18:23,531 --> 01:18:24,938
Good one!

980
01:18:28,235 --> 01:18:32,262
August, boy, you're a hard guy to find.

981
01:18:34,508 --> 01:18:35,936
Been looking everywhere for you.

982
01:18:36,108 --> 01:18:39,402
Excuse me.
You're interrupting a rehearsal here.

983
01:18:39,564 --> 01:18:42,019
WALLACE: Yeah, rehearsal, right.
MAN: And you are...?

984
01:18:42,187 --> 01:18:43,715
Come here to me, son.

985
01:18:53,100 --> 01:18:54,594
Come here.

986
01:18:57,581 --> 01:18:59,369
What'd they do to you?

987
01:19:00,909 --> 01:19:02,337
Nothing.

988
01:19:04,749 --> 01:19:06,657
These people can steal your soul.

989
01:19:07,468 --> 01:19:09,607
Sir, whomever you are,
you don't have the right.

990
01:19:09,772 --> 01:19:12,586
I'm his father, all right?
I have every right.

991
01:19:16,525 --> 01:19:19,175
I'll take you home now. Come on.

992
01:19:19,756 --> 01:19:22,723
But I have a concert. I like it here.

993
01:19:22,893 --> 01:19:25,315
He's a remarkable boy...
WALLACE: You don't think I know that?

994
01:19:25,484 --> 01:19:29,096
What'd you do, you just snatched him up
off the street? That gives you the right?

995
01:19:29,676 --> 01:19:31,847
Wait a moment,
we've been teaching him here.

996
01:19:32,012 --> 01:19:33,190
What are you gonna do?

997
01:19:33,356 --> 01:19:36,901
Fill his head with classical theory
and rules?

998
01:19:37,068 --> 01:19:39,914
You can't learn music from books.

999
01:19:40,075 --> 01:19:41,569
It's out there.

1000
01:19:42,923 --> 01:19:45,193
You teach him? Ha!

1001
01:19:45,612 --> 01:19:47,018
He teaches you.

1002
01:19:47,179 --> 01:19:48,837
You learn from him.

1003
01:19:49,004 --> 01:19:51,393
We are.
I assure you, Mr. Rush, every day.

1004
01:19:52,492 --> 01:19:54,182
You should be with family. Come on.

1005
01:19:57,452 --> 01:19:58,979
Mr. Rush, please.

1006
01:19:59,148 --> 01:20:03,042
Do you have any idea of the importance
of the concert tomorrow night, for August?

1007
01:20:03,820 --> 01:20:05,281
August. Wait, listen.

1008
01:20:05,740 --> 01:20:08,489
You gotta tell me right now,
is this man really your father?

1009
01:20:12,779 --> 01:20:14,535
You can tell me the truth.

1010
01:20:15,659 --> 01:20:17,798
WALLACE:
I know your real name.

1011
01:20:18,924 --> 01:20:20,266
Evan.

1012
01:20:20,844 --> 01:20:22,666
MAN:
August.

1013
01:20:22,827 --> 01:20:24,201
Evan.

1014
01:20:26,507 --> 01:20:28,263
Is he your father?

1015
01:20:28,427 --> 01:20:31,494
[MARK MANCINA'S
"WIZARD RETURNS" PLAYING]

1016
01:20:32,587 --> 01:20:34,692
He taught me everything I know.

1017
01:20:44,747 --> 01:20:46,603
[STRUMS GUITAR]

1018
01:20:46,764 --> 01:20:48,357
ARTHUR:
And we are back, we are back.

1019
01:20:52,044 --> 01:20:54,280
Don't make it harder for yourself, Aug.

1020
01:20:54,444 --> 01:20:56,583
Wizard's not so bad.

1021
01:20:57,804 --> 01:21:00,138
You saw the kid, right?
He's a freak of nature. Yeah.

1022
01:21:00,300 --> 01:21:03,879
Here's the deal. Thousand a night, two
weeks minimum, three cities guaranteed.

1023
01:21:04,044 --> 01:21:06,979
Then we ship him out to your partner
on the West Coast. No.

1024
01:21:07,147 --> 01:21:08,937
ARTHUR:
He just ain't feeling well.

1025
01:21:09,900 --> 01:21:13,065
He said you the only one
who gonna make him feel better.

1026
01:21:19,884 --> 01:21:22,666
Competition. All right, I'll be back.
You do what you do.

1027
01:21:26,412 --> 01:21:28,268
Yo, yo.

1028
01:21:33,868 --> 01:21:36,421
I'm his representation.
That's why I'm making the deal.

1029
01:21:37,229 --> 01:21:39,562
Come on. No, there's no parents.

1030
01:22:08,588 --> 01:22:10,083
Great sounds, kid.

1031
01:22:12,749 --> 01:22:14,276
Gibson J-200?

1032
01:22:15,756 --> 01:22:17,164
It's beautiful.

1033
01:22:17,741 --> 01:22:18,984
Can I see her?

1034
01:22:22,284 --> 01:22:25,131
Hey. It's okay.

1035
01:22:25,580 --> 01:22:27,554
I'm a musician too.

1036
01:22:32,523 --> 01:22:33,985
Yeah.

1037
01:22:37,900 --> 01:22:39,526
Oh, yeah.

1038
01:22:44,588 --> 01:22:47,719
[PLAYING HEITOR PERIERA'S
"DUELING GUITARS"]

1039
01:22:52,588 --> 01:22:53,864
Nice action.

1040
01:22:54,859 --> 01:22:56,136
You're pretty good.

1041
01:22:57,292 --> 01:22:58,852
Thanks.

1042
01:22:59,756 --> 01:23:01,666
See what you can do with mine.

1043
01:24:51,468 --> 01:24:52,811
How long you been playing?

1044
01:24:53,230 --> 01:24:54,571
Six months.

1045
01:24:55,181 --> 01:24:56,904
Six months?

1046
01:24:57,070 --> 01:24:59,458
How'd you learn how to play like that
in six months?

1047
01:24:59,629 --> 01:25:00,644
Juilliard.

1048
01:25:02,222 --> 01:25:03,334
Juilliard?

1049
01:25:03,821 --> 01:25:04,997
Yes, sir.

1050
01:25:05,164 --> 01:25:07,051
I have my own concert tonight.

1051
01:25:08,013 --> 01:25:09,605
Do you reckon I should believe you?

1052
01:25:10,668 --> 01:25:13,221
Yeah. But I can't go.

1053
01:25:13,645 --> 01:25:14,823
Why's that?

1054
01:25:15,533 --> 01:25:17,801
It's kind of a long story.

1055
01:25:20,044 --> 01:25:24,387
Well, if I went to Juilliard
and I had a concert tonight...

1056
01:25:24,557 --> 01:25:26,379
...I wouldn't miss it for the world.

1057
01:25:27,628 --> 01:25:29,003
Yeah.

1058
01:25:33,964 --> 01:25:36,419
But what if something bad
would happen if you did it?

1059
01:25:38,029 --> 01:25:40,134
You never quit on your music.

1060
01:25:40,877 --> 01:25:42,884
No matter what happens.

1061
01:25:43,468 --> 01:25:47,014
Because anytime
something bad happens to you...

1062
01:25:47,404 --> 01:25:50,568
...it's the one place you can escape to
and just, psh, let it go.

1063
01:25:52,621 --> 01:25:54,627
I learned that the hard way.

1064
01:25:56,204 --> 01:25:58,026
And anyway, look at me.

1065
01:25:59,021 --> 01:26:01,258
Nothing bad's gonna happen.

1066
01:26:01,933 --> 01:26:03,973
You gotta have a little faith.

1067
01:26:14,189 --> 01:26:15,367
I'm Louis.

1068
01:26:16,397 --> 01:26:18,699
Ev... August.

1069
01:26:18,861 --> 01:26:20,454
August Rush.

1070
01:26:20,621 --> 01:26:22,596
August Rush.

1071
01:26:23,949 --> 01:26:26,185
Cool name.
WALLACE: August!

1072
01:26:27,468 --> 01:26:28,930
Come on!

1073
01:26:31,885 --> 01:26:33,608
I gotta go, August.

1074
01:26:39,661 --> 01:26:41,090
Bye.

1075
01:26:41,837 --> 01:26:43,244
Yeah.

1076
01:26:45,005 --> 01:26:46,433
Bye.

1077
01:26:55,725 --> 01:26:57,067
Bye.

1078
01:27:14,765 --> 01:27:17,383
Yes, I made him memorize our number.

1079
01:27:19,854 --> 01:27:23,149
I understand. Your department's
doing everything they can.

1080
01:27:41,358 --> 01:27:43,813
Do you think anything bad
happened to him?

1081
01:27:44,877 --> 01:27:46,087
I'm sure he's fine.

1082
01:27:47,117 --> 01:27:49,571
I prayed for him. Did you?

1083
01:27:50,317 --> 01:27:51,910
Yeah.

1084
01:27:53,037 --> 01:27:56,266
Well, if his father loves him like he should...

1085
01:27:56,429 --> 01:27:59,463
...then he'll do what's best for his son.

1086
01:28:01,293 --> 01:28:02,854
You believe that, don't you?

1087
01:28:03,789 --> 01:28:06,473
-Yeah.
-Good.

1088
01:28:06,764 --> 01:28:08,554
Now go get ready.

1089
01:28:08,940 --> 01:28:13,992
[MARK MANCINA'S
"ARPEGGIO THEME" PLAYING]

1090
01:28:19,085 --> 01:28:21,419
<i>DEAN:
Welcome to our Concert in the Park...</i>

1091
01:28:21,869 --> 01:28:26,725
...and the Mercedes Drive Your Future
Scholarship Celebration.

1092
01:28:26,893 --> 01:28:29,446
And now it is with enormous pleasure...

1093
01:28:29,613 --> 01:28:35,778
...that I welcome back to the concert stage
one of Juilliard's own, Lyla Novacek.

1094
01:29:01,358 --> 01:29:05,700
[PLAYING DAVE METZGER'S
"CELLO CONCERTO IN E MINOR"]

1095
01:29:28,142 --> 01:29:29,222
[LOUIS PLAYING LUCAS REYNOLDS'
"SOMETHING INSIDE"]

1096
01:29:29,390 --> 01:29:32,204
<i>[SINGING]
So long you've been running in circles</i>

1097
01:29:32,366 --> 01:29:34,154
<i>Round what's at stake</i>

1098
01:29:37,070 --> 01:29:41,707
<i>But now the time's come
For your feet to stand still in one place</i>

1099
01:29:45,102 --> 01:29:48,582
<i>You wanna reach out
You wanna give in</i>

1100
01:29:48,750 --> 01:29:52,492
<i>Your head's wrapped around
What's around the next bend</i>

1101
01:29:52,654 --> 01:29:57,706
<i>You wish you could find something warm
'Cause you're shivering cold</i>

1102
01:30:00,206 --> 01:30:03,948
<i>It's the first thing you see
As you open your eyes</i>

1103
01:30:04,110 --> 01:30:07,885
<i>The last thing you say
As you're saying goodbye</i>

1104
01:30:08,046 --> 01:30:12,868
<i>But something inside you
ls crying, driving you on</i>

1105
01:30:14,446 --> 01:30:18,602
<i>'Cause if you hadn't found me</i>

1106
01:30:18,766 --> 01:30:21,100
<i>I would have found you</i>

1107
01:30:22,894 --> 01:30:27,913
<i>I would have found you</i>

1108
01:30:35,309 --> 01:30:36,967
I have to go now.

1109
01:30:48,397 --> 01:30:50,120
I'm not coming back this time.

1110
01:30:51,693 --> 01:30:52,970
He's just kidding, Wizard.

1111
01:30:54,509 --> 01:30:57,127
Me and August have a understanding.
Don't we?

1112
01:31:02,062 --> 01:31:04,167
Aug, you can't leave me, man.

1113
01:31:04,334 --> 01:31:06,024
Yes, I can.

1114
01:31:07,214 --> 01:31:09,254
Because you have to
find your parents, right?

1115
01:31:09,421 --> 01:31:12,073
Yeah. My concert's starting.

1116
01:31:12,237 --> 01:31:17,092
Well, all my money's on the fact
your folks won't be able to find you.

1117
01:31:17,262 --> 01:31:18,538
You know why?

1118
01:31:18,926 --> 01:31:20,748
Because they can't hear you.

1119
01:31:21,166 --> 01:31:22,442
They're probably dead.

1120
01:31:22,606 --> 01:31:24,711
You're not going anywhere.

1121
01:31:28,398 --> 01:31:32,774
<i>It's the first thing you see
As you open your eyes</i>

1122
01:31:32,974 --> 01:31:36,236
<i>The last thing you say
As you're saying goodbye</i>

1123
01:31:36,430 --> 01:31:37,445
Nowhere to go, son.

1124
01:31:37,613 --> 01:31:41,061
<i>Something inside you
ls crying and driving you on</i>

1125
01:31:42,062 --> 01:31:47,626
<i>I would have found you</i>

1126
01:31:48,046 --> 01:31:49,737
ARTHUR:
Run, boy.

1127
01:31:49,902 --> 01:31:51,364
Run, August, run.

1128
01:31:51,534 --> 01:31:55,309
<i>I would have found you</i>

1129
01:31:57,551 --> 01:32:02,089
<i>I would have found you</i>

1130
01:32:03,182 --> 01:32:05,287
[HORN HONKS]

1131
01:32:11,630 --> 01:32:13,997
WALLACE:
August!

1132
01:32:26,863 --> 01:32:29,830
[PLAYING DAVE METZGER'S
"CELLO CONCERTO IN E MINOR"]

1133
01:33:02,063 --> 01:33:04,485
WALLACE:
August!

1134
01:33:24,014 --> 01:33:26,534
DEAN:
Thank you, ladies and gentlemen.

1135
01:33:26,894 --> 01:33:32,458
Music has always fascinated us
in the way that it communicates.

1136
01:33:32,621 --> 01:33:35,524
Without words, without pictures.

1137
01:33:36,397 --> 01:33:39,147
And that leads us
to our final performance.

1138
01:33:43,150 --> 01:33:45,223
NICK:
How much longer to the airport?

1139
01:33:45,390 --> 01:33:47,778
MARSHALL:
Man, it jams up the traffic.

1140
01:33:47,951 --> 01:33:50,339
Bring you back to the old days,
eh, Louis?

1141
01:33:52,398 --> 01:33:56,140
[MARK MANCINA'S
"ARPEGGIO THEME" PLAYING]

1142
01:34:07,342 --> 01:34:09,066
"August Rush."

1143
01:34:09,229 --> 01:34:10,986
Evan Taylor.

1144
01:34:26,062 --> 01:34:30,535
Unfortunately, our last performer
seems to have....

1145
01:34:30,703 --> 01:34:33,453
He's here. He's here. He's here.

1146
01:34:33,614 --> 01:34:35,851
Oh. Excellent.

1147
01:34:36,014 --> 01:34:39,724
Perhaps there's no one else
who can better personify...

1148
01:34:39,887 --> 01:34:42,669
...the mystery that is music...

1149
01:34:42,830 --> 01:34:45,448
...than our final composer.

1150
01:35:34,191 --> 01:35:37,770
[ORCHESTRA PLAYING
MARK MANCINA'S "RHAPSODY"]

1151
01:36:32,623 --> 01:36:34,052
Hey, what's that?

1152
01:36:34,223 --> 01:36:36,711
MAN:
Concerts in the Park every spring.

1153
01:37:03,311 --> 01:37:04,904
Let me out.

1154
01:37:06,063 --> 01:37:08,365
Let me out! Let me out!

1155
01:37:54,863 --> 01:37:56,903
<i>HOPE [SINGING]:
Yeah, yeah, yeah</i>

1156
01:38:00,303 --> 01:38:02,059
<i>Woo woo</i>

1157
01:38:04,751 --> 01:38:07,468
<i>Yeah, yeah</i>

1158
01:38:11,311 --> 01:38:13,351
<i>Yeah</i>

1159
01:38:17,232 --> 01:38:20,647
<i>Oh, oh</i>

1160
01:38:21,679 --> 01:38:24,647
<i>Woo</i>

1161
01:38:26,640 --> 01:38:28,712
<i>Yeah</i>

1162
01:38:33,232 --> 01:38:36,199
<i>Oh, oh</i>

1163
01:38:37,742 --> 01:38:38,691
<i>Whoa, oh</i>

1164
01:38:40,334 --> 01:38:42,374
<i>Yeah</i>

1165
01:38:44,398 --> 01:38:48,653
<i>Whoa, oh</i>

1166
01:38:51,118 --> 01:38:54,467
[VAN MORRISON'S
"MOONDANCE" PLAYING]

1167
01:41:39,983 --> 01:41:42,405
<i>AUGUST:
The music is all around us.</i>

1168
01:41:42,575 --> 01:41:46,056
<i>All you have to do is listen.</i>

1169
01:42:00,816 --> 01:42:06,183
<i>MAN [SINGING]:
Ooo eee oooh</i>

1170
01:42:08,112 --> 01:42:12,269
<i>As days go by and fade tonight</i>

1171
01:42:12,431 --> 01:42:15,879
<i>I still question why you left</i>

1172
01:42:16,048 --> 01:42:19,823
<i>I wonder how it didn't work out</i>

1173
01:42:19,984 --> 01:42:21,642
<i>But now you're gone</i>

1174
01:42:21,809 --> 01:42:25,550
<i>And memories are all I have for now</i>

1175
01:42:25,712 --> 01:42:27,468
<i>But no, it's not over</i>

1176
01:42:27,631 --> 01:42:31,428
<i>We'll get older
We'll get over</i>

1177
01:42:31,600 --> 01:42:35,397
<i>We'll live to see the day that I hope for</i>

1178
01:42:35,567 --> 01:42:36,778
<i>Come back to me</i>

1179
01:42:36,943 --> 01:42:38,569
<i>I still believe</i>

1180
01:42:38,737 --> 01:42:43,951
<i>That we'll get it right again</i>

1181
01:42:44,111 --> 01:42:46,533
<i>We'll come back to life again</i>

1182
01:42:46,704 --> 01:42:51,374
<i>We won't say another goodbye again</i>

1183
01:42:51,536 --> 01:42:55,148
<i>Live forever with me</i>

1184
01:42:56,753 --> 01:42:58,824
<i>And someday</i>

1185
01:43:00,688 --> 01:43:02,476
<i>Someday</i>

1186
01:43:02,640 --> 01:43:06,414
<i>We'll be together someday</i>

1187
01:43:08,432 --> 01:43:13,418
<i>Someday we'll be together</i>

1188
01:43:16,048 --> 01:43:19,692
<i>Our someday might be today</i>

1189
01:43:19,856 --> 01:43:23,533
<i>The mysteries of destiny say</i>

1190
01:43:23,697 --> 01:43:27,341
<i>Our somehow and our some way</i>

1191
01:43:27,504 --> 01:43:31,246
<i>For all we know they come tomorrow</i>

1192
01:43:31,408 --> 01:43:35,205
<i>But for today my eyes are open</i>

1193
01:43:35,377 --> 01:43:38,923
<i>My arms are raised for your embrace</i>

1194
01:43:39,088 --> 01:43:43,147
<i>My hands are here to mend what is broken</i>

1195
01:43:43,312 --> 01:43:47,403
<i>To feel again the warmth of your face</i>

